      <td><code>small</code></td>
      <td><code>640px</code>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>medium</code></td>
      <td><code>768px</code>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>large</code></td>
      <td><code>1024px</code>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>x-large</code></td>
      <td><code>1300px</code>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Breakpoint values are accessible via the <code>breakpoint()</code> custom Sass function. However, breakpoints are generally more useful as <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Media_Queries/Using_media_queries">CSS media queries</a>, for which there are the <code>breakpoint-above()</code> and <code>breakpoint-below()</code> custom Sass mixins. Example:</p>
<pre><code class="language-css">@include breakpoint-above(&quot;small&quot;) {
  // Applies only to screen sizes above 640px...
}

@include breakpoint-below(&quot;large&quot;) {
  // Applies only to screen sizes below 1024px...
}
</code></pre>

